\begin_layout Standard
We consider Hartree-Fock as method of choice for extraction of our pseudopotenti
als as it is unbiased in terms of electronic correlation (a sentence was
 added at the beginnig of Section: Pseudo-potential definition).
 On top of it, one can add electronic correlation with any method (DFT,
 CI, etc.).
 We further tested our pseudo-potentials within the CASPT2 framework (end
 of Section: Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\shape slanted
2) Why not B3LYP? This work compares the results obtained using the pseudo-poten
tial model to DFT calculations of the rather popular PBE and PBE0 functionals,
 in addition to the comparably rarely employed TPSS and TPSSh functionals.
 Although the suitability of the B3LYP functional is (rightly) the focus
 of continuing debates in the literature, it still represents one of the
 most influential developments in theoretical/computational chemistry, and
 cannot be ignored.
 For this reason, the authors should also compare to results obtained using
 this method.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We chose one functional for each DFT type to systematically climb the Jacob's
 ladder (one GGA, its hybrid formulation, one meta-GGA and its hybrid formulatio
n).
 We computed the spectra for the polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons for B3LYP
 and since we obtained similar results as for PBE0, we included the B3LYP
 results in the Supporting Information.
\end_layout

